This paper deals with the problem of maintaining a densest subgraph in a dynamic graph, which is a fundamental problem in graph theory and has applications in various fields such as community detection and computational biology. Therefore, it is likely to be classified under cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics). The paper also uses techniques such as sparsification and dual adjustment, which are commonly used in machine learning and optimization, suggesting that it could also be classified under cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) and cs.LG (Machine Learning). Finally, the paper deals with approximation algorithms and worst-case analysis, which are topics in theoretical computer science, indicating that it could also be classified under cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory).
